    "recap_headline": "Baylor",
    "recap_text": "STILLWATER, Okla. \u2013\nRedshirt junior infielder\nTravis Sanders\nhit his first home run of the season for Baylor baseball in a 13-6 loss to Oklahoma State on Sunday afternoon at O'Brate Stadium in Stillwater, Okla.\nThe Cowboys (16-8, 2-4) took the rubber match behind 12 hits offensively and 11 strikeouts on the mound, scoring all 13 of their runs across just three different frames. Though BU (12-11, 2-4) was able to tie things up in the fourth inning at 4-4, OSU pulled away with a five-run home half and another late four-spot.\nSanders was one of three Bears with multiple hits at the plate, joining freshman outfielder\nBrady Janusek\nand redshirt freshman infielder\nBrytton Clements\n. Junior catcher\nJJ Kennett\nalso provided a two-run single, his first multi-RBI effort of the year.\nTHE RUNDOWN\nOklahoma State jumped on Baylor starter\nEthan Calder\nright away for four runs in the bottom of the first on four-straight hits from its 3-4-5-6 hitters. But, Calder was able to settle in and put up back-to-back zeros in the second and third.\nSanders left the yard in the top of the third, a two-run shot that got BU on the board and cut the deficit in half. Then in the top of the fourth, Kennett delivered a game-tying two run single, but that proved to be as close as the Bears would get as the Cowboys countered with five runs of their own in the bottom of the inning to go back in front at 9-4.\nOSU added on in the bottom of the sixth with four more runs on four hits, extending the lead to 13-4.\nBaylor got two back in the top of the seventh on an RBI triple from Janusek, his third knock of the day, and an RBI groundout from redshirt senior first baseman\nTyce Armstrong\n, his team-leading 29\nth\nRBI of the year.\nHIGHLIGHTS\n\u2022 Baylor has not been swept in now 13 consecutive Big 12 series, dating back to May 10-11, 2024, at Oklahoma.\n\u2022 Redshirt junior INF\nTravis Sanders\nextended his on-base streak to 27 games, dating back to 2025.\n\u2022 Sanders launched his first home run of the season, a two-run blast for his fourth multi-RBI game of the year.\n\u2022 Sanders also logged his team-leading 11\nth\nmulti-hit game of the 2026 campaign.\n\u2022 Freshman OF\nBrady Janusek\nextended his hitting streak to four games with a three-hit day, his ninth multi-hit game of the season.\n\u2022 Janusek led the Bears with seven knocks on the week against K-State and OSU.\n\u2022 Redshirt senior 1B\nTyce Armstrong\ndrove in his team-leading 29\nth\nrun of the season.\n\u2022 Redshirt freshman INF\nBrytton Clements\nnotched his fifth multi-hit game of 2026.\n\u2022 Junior C\nJJ Kennett\ntallied his first multi-RBI game of the year.\n\u2022 Redshirt sophomore C\nBrayden Buchanan\nextended his on-base streak to five games.\n\u2022 Senior RHP\nCade Hansen\nlogged his first scoreless relief appearance of the year.\n\u2022 Freshman RHP\nCaldwell McFaddin\nmade his fourth scoreless appearance of the season.\nSTAT OF THE DAY\n376 \u2013 Redshirt junior INF\nTravis Sanders'\nfirst home run of the year traveled 376 feet.\nWHAT'S NEXT\nBaylor (12-11, 2-4 Big 12) returns home for a midweek matchup against Incarnate Word (13-11) on Tuesday, March 24. First pitch is scheduled for 6:30 p.m. from Magnolia Field at Baylor Ballpark in Waco.\nTo stay up to date on all things Baylor baseball, follow the team on its official Facebook, Twitter and Instagram accounts: @BaylorBaseball.\n-BaylorBears.com-",
